–Male":"1168–Zesnulý","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28. srpna 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28. august 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Afdød","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28. august 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28 augustus 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Overleden","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28 augustus 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28 August 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Deceased","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28 August 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coffin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southwestern England, of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Middle English <i>cofin</i>, <i>coffin</i>, Old French <i>cof(f)in</i> (from Late Latin <i>cophinus</i>, Greek <i>kophinos</i>) ‘container, basket; coffer, chest (for keeping treasures, documents, armour, etc.)’. Early bearers of this as a hereditary surname were of knightly rank. Old French <i>cofin</i> was synonymous with <i>coffer</i>, and it may be that <i>Cofin</i> was used to denote a keeper of the (royal) coffer, attested in Anglo-Latin <i>cofferarius</i>. Compare   Coffer  . The modern English word <i>coffin</i> is a specialized development of this term, not attested until the 16th century.","History: Tristram Coffin came from Brixham, Devon, to Haverhill, MA, before 1647. An important line of his descendants is associated with Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Coffer","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>cofre</i>, <i>coffre</i>, <i>coffer</i> ‘box, chest’ (from Old French <i>cof(f)rehere</i>), used to denote a box or coffer maker (Old French <i>coffrier</i>), perhaps also for a treasurer.","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Kaufer   or <b>Kauffer</b>."]},{"name":"Coffing","meanings":["English: variant of   Coffin  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Coffin II was born in 1209, in Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Richard Coffyn I. He had at least 2 sons. He died on 28 August 1254, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28. august 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28. august 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28. elokuuta 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Kuollut","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28. elokuuta 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28 août 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Décédé","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","28 August 1254":"28 août 1254","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Richard Coffin II est né en 1209, à Alwington, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Sir Richard Coffyn I. Il a eu au moins 2 fils. Il est décédé le 28 août 1254, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 45 ans."},"de":{"1209–28 August 1254":"1209–28. August 1254","1209–1254":"1209–1254","1224–1275":"1224–1275","1225–1318":"1225–1318","1168–Male":"1168–Verstorben","1225":"1225","1